'''First Lady from Plains''' is a 1984 autobiography by [[Rosalynn Carter]].<ref name="Hannan1999">{{cite book|author=Caryn Hannan|title=Georgia Biographical Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y8QGF2QH5K0C|date=1 January 1999|publisher=State History Publications|isbn=978-1-878592-42-2|page=156}}</ref> It is divided into 12 chapters.<ref name="Sibley2016">{{cite book|author=Katherine A.S. Sibley|title=A Companion to First Ladies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=77u4CwAAQBAJ|date=2 March 2016|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-73224-3}}</ref>

Gaddis Smith reviewed the book for the journal ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' and wrote that "These earnest, well-constructed memoirs depict a determined and informed politician who played a significant role as her husband's closest adviser".<ref name=FA84>{{cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/1984-06-01/first-lady-plains|title=First Lady from Plains|date=1984|work=[[Foreign Affairs]]|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>

